NORMALISED EXTRACT
Problem: count set bits (population count) in an integer
Algorithms (concrete)
1. Naive bit scan
   count = 0
   while n > 0:
     count += n & 1
     n = n >>> 1
   Complexity: O(w) where w is word width.
2. Kernighan's algorithm (recommended when few bits set)
   count = 0
   while n != 0:
     n = n & (n - 1)
     count += 1
   Complexity: O(k) where k is number of set bits.
3. Table lookup (8-bit chunks)
   table[0..255] precomputed
   sum table[(n >> 0) & 0xff] + table[(n >> 8) & 0xff] + ...
4. SWAR (parallel) for 32-bit
   u = u - ((u >>> 1) & 0x55555555)
   u = (u & 0x33333333) + ((u >>> 2) & 0x33333333)
   u = (u + (u >>> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F
   count = (u * 0x01010101) >>> 24
5. Compiler intrinsics / hardware
   Use __builtin_popcount / POPCNT instruction when available.
BigInt handling
- For BigInt, use repeated Kernighan with BigInt arithmetic or split into fixed-size limbs (32/64-bit) and apply chunked methods.
